  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Postscript to Kim Gyeongji's Poetry Collection
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the Gyechuk year, I returned from the mountains. My friend Kim Gyeongji came calling at my modest lodgings and said to me: "During my inspection tour of the eastern provinces, my companions honored my departure with prefaces and poems, showering me with their regard. Yet you alone—like a wild goose and swallow that never meet—have offered me not a single word. This weighs upon my heart. I beg you, write a postscript to my collected poems." He withdrew a scroll from his sleeve and showed it to me. All of it was written by great brushes of our time.

    Regarding Gyeongji's talents, his virtue, his excellence—and the praise and encouragement of all these distinguished writers—there is nothing left unsaid. Who would dare add more words to such completeness? Yet I have long heard it said: "To one who has seen the ocean, it is difficult to speak of water; to one who has walked in the presence of sages, it is difficult to speak of learning."

    Gyeongji was born into a family of merit and honor, and has wandered freely through the gardens of moral cultivation and literary art. Now, bearing imperial commission to the eastern lands and observing the splendor of distant regions, his spirit grows ever more expansive, his bearing more noble and majestic. That we humble companions should await his return with renewed eyes—this is surely no exaggeration.

    How dare I compare a hoofprint's worth of water to the boundless sea? How dare I measure an anthill against towering mountains? How dare I offer coarse fare when fine delicacies are served? How dare I bring a reed pipe where a silk lute plays? To do so would mark me either a fool or a madman—surely inviting ridicule.

    This is why my brush, each time I began to write, would falter and stop. Yet Gyeongji's request has come twice now, and so I offer this postscript, hoping merely to discharge my duty.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Gyechuk year (계축년): This refers to 1613 in the lunar calendar, during the Joseon Dynasty''s Gwanghaegun period.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Eastern provinces (關東): The Gwandong region, referring to areas east of the capital.'
  - key: ''
    value: The metaphor of goose and swallow represents ships passing in the night—two people failing to meet despite being meant to.
  - key: ''
    value: The classical allusion about the ocean and water, and sage and learning, comes from Confucian texts expressing the idea that profound experience makes it difficult to be impressed by lesser knowledge.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hoofprint in water, anthill compared to mountains, coarse fare versus delicacies, reed pipe versus silk lute: These are traditional Chinese humility formulas expressing the writer''s self-deprecation before undertaking the task.'
